            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real branded hashtag examples</h2>

        <h3>1. DTC skincare — 3x saves and shares</h3>
        <p>A skincare brand tested three branded-hashtag formats over 90 days: brand + benefit (#GlowRoutine), brand + community (#OurGlowCrew), and campaign moment (#GlowWeek). The community format drove <strong>3x more saves and shares</strong> than the other two combined and became the brand's permanent evergreen tag.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B LinkedIn consultant — 200 to 2,000 views</h3>
        <p>A B2B consultant paired one branded LinkedIn hashtag with a weekly post ritual. Post reach climbed from ~200 views to 2,000+ within 12 weeks as followers used the tag to find prior posts and shared the tag in their own networks.</p>

        <h3>3. Local restaurant — 15K-person following</h3>
        <p>A single-location restaurant built a branded hashtag around a specific menu item and encouraged diners to post using it. Two years of consistent seeding produced a 15,000-post archive that ranks the restaurant #1 for their local category search — a compounding SEO effect from a social tag.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Branded hashtag vs. generic hashtag — when to use each</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Branded hashtag</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Only your brand's posts appear</li>
              <li>Aggregates UGC and social proof</li>
              <li>Compounds over years</li>
              <li>You control the space</li>
              <li>Example: #ShareACoke, #JustDoIt</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Generic / category hashtag</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Discovery within a broader topic</li>
              <li>Competes with the whole category</li>
              <li>Reach depends on the algorithm</li>
              <li>Shared attention with rivals</li>
              <li>Example: #skincare, #saas, #b2b</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Use both. Category hashtags fetch new eyeballs. Branded hashtags convert them into a repeatable community pattern.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 branded hashtag best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keep it under 20 characters.</strong> Mobile typing kills long tags. #ShareACoke wins; #ShareACocaColaMoment doesn't.</li>
          <li><strong>Test-search before launch.</strong> Confirm the tag returns zero or negligible results. Piggybacking on someone else's tag pollutes your feed.</li>
          <li><strong>Anchor it in every touchpoint.</strong> Bio, campaigns, packaging, email, ads, creator briefs — no exceptions.</li>
          <li><strong>Seed with paid creators for 30-90 days.</strong> A tag with 8 uses at day 30 will die. Engineer initial gravity via brand deals.</li>
          <li><strong>Prompt UGC with clear instructions.</strong> "Post your setup with <code>#OurTag</code> for a chance to be featured." Explicit beats subtle.</li>
          <li><strong>Track weekly, not monthly.</strong> Volume, reach, sentiment, top contributors, ratio of brand vs. organic posts.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-share the best UGC.</strong> Every re-share teaches new users the tag is worth using. Silent brands starve the feed.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — half-hearted execution</div>
          <p>The single biggest failure mode is treating a branded hashtag as a one-time launch. If it isn't in the bio, on every post, in every creator brief, and in every email footer, it will not achieve escape velocity. Consistency is the entire game.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common branded hashtag mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Launching without testing collisions.</strong> Overlapping with an existing tag ruins tracking and confuses users.</li>
          <li><strong>Overloading with too many tags.</strong> Three campaign tags at once dilute each of them. Pick one hero tag per campaign.</li>
          <li><strong>Not featuring UGC.</strong> Users stop tagging if their posts are never acknowledged.</li>
          <li><strong>No measurement system.</strong> If you can't quote weekly volume and sentiment, you can't optimize.</li>
          <li><strong>Killing an evergreen tag prematurely.</strong> Branded tags compound over 2-5 years. Do not swap it every campaign.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps brands turn hashtag mentions into search demand</h2>
        <p>A branded hashtag builds social proof. But search demand is where the money is — every time a user sees your hashtag and later Googles the brand, they land on a page you need to have optimised. theStacc audits the pages your <a href="/glossary/branded-keywords/">branded keywords</a> land on, closes the ranking gaps, and turns the awareness your hashtag creates into revenue-attributable organic traffic. Social + search compound together — most brands run them as separate silos and leave money on the table.</p>

